            <div class="faq-topic-panel visible" id="faq-panel-accounting">
                <h3 class="faq-panel-heading">Core Concepts of Accounting</h3>
                <div class="faq-responsive-grid">
                    <details class="faq-disclosure-card">
                        <summary>
                            <span class="faq-badge">?</span>
                            <span class="faq-question-text">What is accountancy?</span>
                            <svg class="faq-icon-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5"/></svg>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p><strong>Accountancy</strong> is the systematic practice of recording, measuring, classifying, summarising, and communicating financial information about an organization. It forms the technical operational framework backing corporate finance teams globally.</p>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="faq-disclosure-card">
                        <summary>
                            <span class="faq-badge">?</span>
                            <span class="faq-question-text">What is the definition of accounting?</span>
                            <svg class="faq-icon-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5"/></svg>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p><strong>Accounting</strong> is the language of business. It translates economic activities into structured datasets by identifying, logging, and issuing standard financial reports to interested stakeholders.</p>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="faq-disclosure-card">
                        <summary>
                            <span class="faq-badge">?</span>
                            <span class="faq-question-text">What are the 3 types of account?</span>
                            <svg class="faq-icon-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5"/></svg>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Under the traditional classification rules, accounts are divided into:</p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><strong>Personal Account:</strong> Deals with entities/people. (Debit receiver, Credit giver)</li>
                                <li><strong>Real Account:</strong> Assets and properties. (Debit what comes in, Credit what goes out)</li>
                                <li><strong>Nominal Account:</strong> Expenses, revenue, gains, losses. (Debit expenses, Credit income)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                    <details class="faq-disclosure-card">
                        <summary>
                            <span class="faq-badge">?</span>
                            <span class="faq-question-text">What are the 4 major accounts in accounting?</span>
                            <svg class="faq-icon-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5"/></svg>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>Modern accounting frameworks recognize: Assets, Liabilities, Equity (Capital), and Revenue/Expenses. They govern the master equation: <em>Assets = Liabilities + Equity</em>.</p>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-topic-panel" id="faq-panel-acca">
                <h3 class="faq-panel-heading">Understanding ACCA</h3>
                <div class="faq-responsive-grid">
                    <details class="faq-disclosure-card span-full">
                        <summary>
                            <span class="faq-badge">?</span>
                            <span class="faq-question-text">What is ACCA certification?</span>
                            <svg class="faq-icon-chevron" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path d="M5 8l5 5 5-5"/></svg>
                        </summary>
                        <div class="faq-answer-content">
                            <p>The Association of Chartered Certified Accountants is a globally recognized professional qualification based in the UK. To achieve membership status, a student must clear 13 professional examinations, complete a specialized Ethics module, and acquire 3 years of verified practical experience.</p>
                        </div>
                    </details>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="faq-topic-panel" id="faq-panel-ca">
